{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/00280605207/1948123001/0350.xml":{"full_text":"D. C. Securities Score\nSharp 1948 Advances\nOn Counter Market\nBy Edward C. Stone\nCapital securities sold over the\ncounter registered some sharp gains\nduring the year, the advances being\nheaded by Barber Ross common,\nup from 50 to 100; District National\nSecurities preferred. 80 to 97: Lin\ncoln Service common. 22'< to 30, and\nMerchants Transfer preferred. Ill\nto 117.\nConsolidated Title Co. common\nended the year at 30, up 5 points;\nD. C. Paper Mills common moved\nfrom l7g to 3'\u00bb, Federal Storage\ncommon. Seaboard Finance pre\nferred, Griffiths Consolidated pre\nferred and common, were among\nother issues changed very little in\nthe 12 months.\nBids for bank stocks disclosed\nfew changes, a survey reveals, al\nthough quotations on some of these\nshares worked lower. Bank stocks\nsold over the counter include Ana\ncostia National, City Bank. Bank\nof Silver Spring, Hamilton National,\nSecurity Savings Commercial,\nMunsev Trust. National Metropol\nitan. Industrial and Suburban Na\ntional.\nDistrict Theaters. Mayflower Ho\ntel common and Washington Prop\nerties were among \"counter\u201d stocks\ncarrying lower bids at the year end.\nBonds were little changed. Racquet\nClub 3s lost ground, dropping from\n78 to a bid of 73. Trading volume\nin these unlisted securities has been\nabout the same as in 1947, dealers\nsaid today.\nLower Food Costs forecast.\nFarms and factories will produce\nas much food in 1949 as in the rec\nord year 1948. and consumers prob\nably will pay less for it. John A.\nHartford, president of the Great\nAtlantic Pacific Tea Co., pre\ndicted today. Food prices have de\nclined steaoily since July, he said.\nIn a forecast from headquarters\nof the Atlantic division, Baltimore,\nMr. Hartford cited two major de\nflationary factors in the food price\npicture: Continued high production\nand \u201csoft\u201d markets: fewer con\nsumer food dollars and greater\ncompetition for them.\n\u201cOnce again we have entered a\nperiod when the purse as well as 'he\nappetite will determine what food\nand how much of it people will buy.\u201d\nhe said. \u201cMore and more consumer\ndollars are going into payments for\nhouses, automobiles, television sets\nand other things, and fewer dollars\nare available for food. This means\nthat 1949 will see keener competi\ntion for the consumers' food dollar.\u201d\nDemand Deposits Decline.\nChristmas requirements for funds\nwere one reason for a drop of $15,\n741.000 in demand deposits in Wash\nington banks during the week ended\nDecember 22. the Richmond Reserve\nBank reported today. Time deposits\nwere off slightly.\nCommercial loans were up $1,082.\n000. with real estate loans practically\nunchanged. Reserves with the Fed\neral Reserve Bank were substantially\nhigher. Total assets declined.\nHugh Fulton. Washington and\nNew York lawyer, has been ap\nDointed general counsel for the Hud\nson Manhattan Railroad Co it j\nwas announced today. From 1938\nto 1941 he served as special assistant j\nto the Attorney General and for the!\nnext three years was chief counsel I\nand head of the Truman Senate]\nCommittee.\nMore than $3,300,000,000 of life,\ninsurance funds went into the j\nfinancing of real estate mortgages\nduring 1948. a new record, and up\n$600,000,000 from 1947, the Institute\nof Life Insurance reported today.\nBusiness Briefs I\nBank Clearing? in 25 leading cities]\ndeclined to $13,704,863,000 in the]\nholidav week ended December 29]\nvs $15,997,796,000 in the preceding]\nfull week nad $12,986,161,000 in the]\nlike 1947 week\u2014Dun Bradstreet.\nBusiness Loans of member banks j\nIn leading cities totaled $15,614,000,\n000 on December 22, a gain of $19,\n000.000 from a week earlier and\n$816,000,000 above a year earlier\u2014\nFederal Reserve Board.\nCrude Oil Production averaged\n5.640.750 barrels daily in the week\nended December 25 vs. 5.645.250 in\nthe previous week and 5.285,440 in\nthe like 1947 week\u2014American Petro-\nleum Institute.\nBethlehem Steel Corp. disclosed\nplans to market $50,000,000 of 30-\nyear bonds in January and 627,960\ncommon shares when market condi-\ntions are favorable. Proceeds will j\nbe used for expansion. Both issues]\nwill be offered publicly.\nConsolidated Edison Co. registered\nwith the SEC $50,000,000 of first\nmortgage refunding bonds to be j\nsold at competitive bidding to\nfinance property additions and con- j\nstruction. The company will retire i\n$40,000,000 of short-term bank\nloans.\nI'nited Light Railways Co. re\nceived SEC permission to establish\na $50,551,818 reserve. The company\nwill make charges against these\nfunds to cover financing necessary\nto liquidate itself in compliance\nwith the Holding Company Act.\nGreat Northern Railway earned\n$23,602,876 or $7.63 a share in 11\nmonths ended November 30 vs. $21,\n640.060 or $7 a year earlier.\nNorthern Pacific Railway net in\ncome for 11 months ended November\n30 was $8,639,619 or $3.48 vs. $9\n782.746 or $3.94 in the same 1947\nperiod.\nChicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul\nPacific Rafiroad earned $5,411,831\n.jn 11 months ended November 30\nvs. $5,144,072 a year earlier.\nNorth American Aviation, Inc.,\nnet income for 12 months ended\nSeptember 30 was $6,779,561 or $1.97\nvs. a deficit of $28,259 in the pre\nceding fiscal period.\nMurray Corp. of America earned\n$1,158,976 or $1,17 in three months\nended November 30 vs. $959,312 or\n95 cents a year earlier.\nJohn Morrell Co. profit for 12\nmonths ended October 30 was $2,\n587.741 or $3.23 vs. $2,889,017 or $3.61\nin the preceding fiscal period.\nBeatrice Foods Co. net for nine\nmonths ended November 30 was $2.\n306.349 or $4,21 vs. $1,984,056 or $3.57\nIn the same 1947 period.\nPittsburgh West Virginia Rail\nway earned $1,377,442 or $4.52 in 11\nmonths ended November 30 vs.\n$664,404 or $2.18 a year earlier.\nAmerican Distilling Co. profit for\n12 months ended September 30 was\n$1,030,603 or $4.12 vs. $1,010,386 or\n$4.04 in the preceding fiscal period.\nGeneral Box Co. earned $786,452\nor 43 cents in nine months ended\nSeptember 30 vs. $1,200,746 or 69\ncents a year earlier.\nMid-Continent Airline* reported a\ndeficit of $23,852 for 11 months\nended November 30 vs. net income\n\u00abf $81,671 In the sam* 1947 period.\nI N. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE\n(Furnished by the Associated Press.)\nSales\nStock and Add Net\nDividend Rate. 00. High Low 1:15. chfe\nABBOTT L2.60b 2 7014 7014 7014\nA C F-Brill Mot 6 274 214 214\nAcme Steel 4 1 46 46 46 *4\nAdams Ex 1 lOe 3 181b 1814 1814\nAddressog-M 2a 8 2814 28*4 2814 44\nAdmiral Cd 60a 22 1914 19*4 1914\nAir Reduction 1 29 1914 19 19+14\nAlaska Juneau 5 3 3 3\nAldens Inc 1' t 8 14*4 1414 1414 Vs\nAlleghany Corn J i 21b 214 2*4\nAlleghanv Cp pf 5 4714 47*4 47*4\nAlleg-Lud Stl 2e 11 241b 24*4 241b\nAllied C&Dye 6a 5 181 180 181 +3\nAllied Mills 2a 3 26*4 26*4 26*4 *4\nAllied Strs 3 12 28*4 2714 28*4 lb\nAllis Chaim 1 60 25 27*4 26*4 2674 Vb\nAllis Chal pf 3*,4 2 77 77 77\nAlpha Port C 2e 5 27 27 27 >4\nAmalLeath .30p 2 314 3*4 3*4\u201c *4\nAmerada Pet 3a 5 92 9014 92\nAm Agricul 3a 3 33*4 35*4 35*4+ *4\nAm Airlines 52 71b 7*4 714 *4\nAm Airl pf 3*4 5 55*4 55 55 *4\nAmBankN l.BOa 8 20*/a 20*4 20*4- \u20184\nAm Bosch le 11*4 1014 1014\u2014 lb\nAmBrakeSh2*ae 13 32*4 3114 311b\u2014 *4\nAm Broadcast 50 914 9*4 9*4 *4\nAm Cable Rad 33 3*4 3*4 3*4 *4\nAm Can 3a 5 81*4 8114 81*4 *4\n+Am Can of 7 20 173 173 173\nAm CarArFdv 3e 7 31*4 31*4 31*4- *4\nAmCrysSug 1 20 3 15*4 15*4 15*4\nAmCyamidl\u2019aa 9 4014 40 40*4+ *4\nAmCyamid3'4pf 2 100*4 100 100*4 14\nAm Distillers 2 1 30*4 30*4 30*4 14\nAm Encaust '4& 2 51b 5*4 3*4\nAm Export L 2 20 14 1314 14 >4\nAm fc Frgn Pwr 8 174 114 114 *4\nA&FPurTpfo'sk 5 45 4414 44*4 *4\nAm*FP46pf4'4 6 39 38*4 3814+ >4\nAmdtF Pwr 2 pf 7 614 6*4 614\nAm Hide Lea 3 314 3*a 314 \u20184\nAm Home 1.20a 3 25*a 25*4 25*4+ *4\nAm Ice 60e 1 514 514 514 \u20184\nAm Loro 1 40 24 1714 17 17\nAm Mch&