x\u2019ra or extras, a Paid so far this year.\np Paid in 1948__\nNew York Produce\nNEW YORK. Dec. 30 i4\u00bb.\u2014Butter\nfirm. Wholesale prices on bulk\ncartons Creamery, higher than 92 score\nand premium marks iAA\u00bb. 6.12'. score\n(A\u00bb. 66: 90 score \u00abB\u00bb. 65: 89 score <C\u00bb.\n6;$3* (New tubs usually command\na pound over the bulk carton price\nCheese\u2014196.54;$: steady, prices un-,\nchanges.\nSteadiness predominated today in the\nwholesale egg market. Receipts totaled\n19.219 cases. Spot quotations follow:\nMidwestern. Mixed colors\u2014Fancy heavy\nweights. 60: extra l large. 58: extra 2\nlaree. 55-56: extra 1 medium. 48-49:\npullets. 45Va: current receipts. 50-51:\ndirnes. 48: checks. 45-47.\nWhites\u2014Fancy heavyweights. 61-6^:\nextra 1 larae. 59**i-60: extra 2 large, n6\n58. extra 1 medium, 50-51.\nBrowns\u2014Fancy heavyweights. 60: extra\n1 large. 58: extra 2 larae. 55-56; extra 1\nmedium. 48-49\nNearby (Ton quotations on nearby white\nand brown *ic* reoresent highest wholesale\nselling prices for the finest marks available\nand not oavine Drire*. to producer* or\nshippers): Whites\u2014Extra fancy heavy\nweights. 64-65: fancy heavyweights. 62-6.$:\nmediums. 52-59: pullets. 40-48.\nBrowns\u2014Extra fancy heavyweights 61\n62: fancy heavyweights. 60 mediums.\n50-51; pullets. 46-47.__\nChicago Livestock\nCHICAGO. DfC. 30 \u2014Salable live\nstock receipts at principal markets to\nHoas. Catlie. Sheep\nChicago 13.000 2.500 1.500\nKansas City 2.5oo 1.000 1200\nOmaha 14.500 2,500 2.000\nEast St. Louia 12.000 l.gno 2.000\nSt. Joseph _ 7.000 1.200 1.500\nSioux City _ 1 1.000 2.700 300\nSouth St. Paul 14.000 2.500 2.500\nIndianapolis 10.500 1.000 3.000\nCincinnati _ 2.000 300 loo\nFort Worth flop 800 2.000\nPeoria fi.noo 300 400\nThe Chicago hog market opend slow\ntoday under the pressure over overnight\nreceipts consisting of 13.000 salable head\nand fs.000 consigned direct to packers.\nTraders had expected only 7.000 Good\nand choice butchers sold in the early\ntrade at $22 to *22.50. the early (op. or\ngenerally 30 cents lower than yesterday\nCattle and sheep were called higher.\nDividends Announced\nNEW YORK. Dec. 30 i\u00a3v\u2014Dividends\ndeclared:\nPe- Stork of Pay\nRale. rlod. record, able.\nIrregular.\nAm Light A Trac 30c .j. 1-14 2-1\nLowell Bteachery 50e 1-5 1-12\nExtra.\nBartgis Eros A Co 60c 12-31 1-14\nRegular.\nBartgis Bros A Co 5r Q 12-31 1-14\nHercules Powder pf $1.25 Q 2-4 2-15\nMarket Averages\nSTOCKS. 30 lb 16 00\nIndst. Kalla. Util. Btks.\nNet Change- .3 unc. .4 .3\nToday noon_ 89.0 39.r 39.4 05.0\nPrey, day_ 89.3 39.1 39.0 64.7\nWeek ago_ 88.7 38.8 38.9 84.3\nMonth ago_ 87.0 39.0 38.8 83.0\nYear ago_ 91.8 37 6 40.1 88.7\n1948 high_ 98.7 48.1 42.3 72.4\n1948 low_ 83.3 34.2 38.0 60.3\nBONDS. 20 10 10 1010 Low\nRaUs. indst. Util. Pgn. Yield.\nNet change unr. unc. unc. +.2 unc.\nToday noon 90.0 1 01.9 100 6 82.9 108,5\nPrev. day._ 90.0 101J) 100.6 62.7 198.5\nWeek ago 89.7 101.6 100.3 82.4 108.1\nMonth ago 89.8 101.1 99.8 61 8 10,.9\nYear ago 87 6 99.7 9* 0 66.7 106 9\n194* high 93.7 101.0 102 0 66.9 1I06j\n194* low 87.7 99.8 P8.0 80 2 107.01\n(Compiled bx the Agiociated Press.1\nEconomists Session\nHears Mixed Reports\nOn Business Outlook\nfty the Associated Press\nCLEVELAND. Dec. 30.\u2014Business\nforecasts for 1949 took a mixed tone\namong speakers before economists\nmeeting here.\nThe American Statistical Associa\ntion heard a variety of ideas on\n1949 prospects, and the American\nEconomic Association heard one\nspeaker warn against the continued\ndanger of inflation.\nThe statisticians were told by\nDonald B. Woodward of New York,\nvice president of the Mutual Life\nInsurance Co., that the odds in 1949\nare for the start of a business j\ndecline.\nRail Layoffs Predicted.\nThese expressions came after a\nChesapeake Ohio Railroad official\nsaid here yesterday that layoffs for\nthe entire rail industry are in pros\npect next year because of a decline\nin freight and passenger traffic. At\nleast two other roads were indicated\nto be experiencing a slump. But in\nPhiladelphia, a Pennsylvania Rail\nroad spokesman said the line\u2014one\nof Nation\u2019s largest\u2014\u2019\u2019is not planning\nany reduction in personnel\u201d in the\nimmediate future.\nRegarding the 1949 business out\nlook, Mr. Woodward said:\n\"This decline will be sufficiently\nlimited so that most Americans -will\nknow of it only from their news\npapers and not from personal ex\nperience.\u201d\nBut in the following year, he\nadded, the downward move would\nassume serious proportions.\nWar Economy Seen.\nPlank D. Newberry, consultant for\nWestinghouse Electric Corp., Pitts\nburgh, said there will be a change\nin the present high level of business\nactivity. The Nation's economy will\nmove toward a war economy, he said.\nRussell Weisman, associate editor\nof the Cleveland Plain Dealer, told\nj the statisticians \u201cmost of the forces\n!of the boom of the last three years\nhave spent themselves. Easy money\nhas run out.\u201d\nSpeaking before the American\nEconomic Association also meeting\nhere today. Seymour E. Harris, eco\ni nomics professor of Harvard Univer\nj sity. said that \"even if 1949 is a year\nof balance or, as many predict, a\nyear of declining prices, guards\nagainst inflation must be strength\nened.\"\nRoss Marshall, a senor vice presi\ndent of the C. O., made the pre\ndiction here yesterday regarding:\nwidespread rail layoffs next year in\nannouncing that total layoffs by his\nline would reach 5,500 by January 1.\nVirginia Railway Has Cut.\nThe New York, New Haven\nHartford Railroad also announced\nan \u201cextensive\u201d reduction in per\nsonnel, but did not divulge the num\nber involved.\nAt Norfolk, Va\u201e \"the usual sea\nsonal curtailment\" was announced\nby the Virginia Railway. No figures\nwere released.\nMr. Marshall said. \"The main\ncause is a decline in business vol\nume which began in November.\"\nPointing out that the C. O. was\na coal-carrying road, he declared\nit loaded only 3,550 coal cars Tues\nday, compared, with 5,000 to 5,500\ndally \u201cbefore the slow-down.\u201d\nCoal production in the United\nStates is satisfying the country\u2019s\npresent requirements, he said, and\nGreat Britain, France, Germany\nand Poland are mining more coal.\n\u201cThey aren't going to buy it here\nif they can satisfy their own needs,\u201d\nMr. Marshall added. \u201cI don't think\nwe'll export any coal to Europe in\nthree years.\u201d\nRegarding passenger curtail\nments, he said the line would con\nsolidate two of its George Wash\ning trains and resort trains from\nChicago to Detroit would be cut1\nfrom six to three weekly next sum\nmer.\nHenry Ford II Expects\nBuyers' Market Soon\n\u2022y th\u00ab Associated Press\nDETROIT. Dec. 30.\u2014Optimism is\nexpressed by Henry Ford II in his\nyear-end statement.\nThe Ford Motor Co. president said\ntoday that conditions indicate a\nbuyers\u2019 market is not far away. He\nadded that his company would wel\ncome this.\nThe automobile company execu\ntive pointed out that Ford re\ndesigned its products this year with\nan eye to coming competition in a\nbuvers\u2019 market.\n\u2022\u2018It\u2019s going to take a buyers\u2019;\nmarket and tough competitive sell\ning to give Ford the sales-leader\nship we are after,\u201d Mr. Ford said.\nHe termed this year's introduc\ntion of an entirely new line of cars\nwith a minimum of layoffs during\nthe changeover \u201cthe high point of\nthe year.\u201d\nThe company spent approximately\n$100,000^000 redesigning its Ford,\nLincoln and Mercury models this\nyear and Mr. Ford said no major\nmodel changes are planned for 1949.\nMr. Ford said he believed the\nauto industry probably would pro\nduce more units in 1949 than it did\nin 1948. but he indicated the in\ncrease probably would not be very\ngreat.\nHe said a tight steel supply, the\nEuropean relief program and pos\nsible defense requirements might\nhold down the 1949 output of the\nindustry.\nOfficial of General Mills\nWeds Polish Countess\nly the Associated Press\nMINNEAPOLIS. Dec. 30.\u2014Start\ning a brief honeymoon today were\nHarry A. Bullis. board chairman of\nGeneral Mills, tnc., and his bride,\nthe Countess Maria Smorczewska.\nformerly -of Warsaw and Vilno,\nPoland.\nIt was the third marriage for Mrs.\nBullis. who is 54. For the bride\ngroom. 58. it was the second.\nMrs. Bullis was active in the War-!\nsaw underground after Nazi armies,\noverrand her estate in 1940. She\ncame to this country in January,\n1947. Shortly afterward, following\nthe death of Mr. Bullis\u2019 wife, she\ntook over management of his house\nhold.\nOnly a few relatives and close\nfriends were present at the cere\nmony last night. Among them were\nArthur Bliss Lane, former Ambas\nsador to Poland, and his wife, who\nbecame friendly with Mrs. Bullis\nduring their stay in Warsaw. Also\npresent was a daughter of the bride.\nMrs. Grazyna Prosinska, London,\nEngland, who was seeing her mother\nfor the first time in 10 years.\n18 From Ship That Broke\nIn Two Land in Norfolk\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nNORFOLK, Va\u201e Dec. 30 \u2014Eight\neen survivors of the Argentine Navy\nvessel, El Capitan, which broke in\ntwo in the Atlantic Sunday, have\narrived safely here.\nThe Coast Guard cutter Cherokee\ndocked with the survivors yesterday\nand with the stern of the vessel in\ntow.\nThe El Capitan w-as off the North\nCarolina coast at the time of the\naccident. She was being towed from\nSavannah, Ga., to Baltimore, where\nshe was to undergo repairs. The\nbow of the ship was taken to Balti\nmore.\nSixteen of the 18 survivors wer\u00ae\ntaken from the bow of the ship.\nTime Designates Truman\nAs 1948'Man of the Year'\nBy the Associated Prtss\nNEW YORK, Dec. 30\u2014President\nTruman is Time Magazine's \"Man\nof the Year\u201d for 1948. It is the\nsecond time he has been so honored\nby the news magazine.\nTime said in its January 3 issue\nreleased today\u2014that the President's\nelection \u201cwas a personal victory al\nmost without historical parallel; a\nvictory of the fighting spirit.\u201d\nMr. Truman was selected by Time\nas \u201cMan of the Year\u201d for 1945, the\nyear of the atom bomb. The maga\nzine said it chose Mr. Truman then\nbecause the president \"somewhat\nunwittingly, somewhat against his\nown will, became more than any\nother man responsible for the bomb.\nGEORGE I. BORGER\nLoans on Real Estate\nSales, Rentals, Insurance\n643 Indiana Artnu* N W.\nNA. 0350\nOPPORTUNITY TO GO\nINTO BUSINESS\nOne of the oldest and best known\nmanufacturers of paint products\nwill sell, on favorable basis, fully\nequipped store in Washington, D. C\u201e\nselling paint, wallpaper and sundries\nto retail and wholesale trade. Will\nshow you how to operate profitably\nthrough thoroughly tested methods\nwith a capital investment as low as\n$5,000.\nBox 234-L, Stor\nFIRST TRUST\nMONEY\nLOW Ratet\nLong Term\nHost*, Apirtnnb aid\nIivestnrat PropartM\nFHA LOANS\nBOSS ft PHELPS\nMORTGAGE CO.\n.1417 K St N.W. HA. \u00bb3M\nSolve Your\nHousing Problem\nBUY\nYOUR\nHOME\nIf you hove the necessary down\npayment, our modern, stream\nlined direct reduction plan will\nhelp you buy a home.\nInterest, principal, taxes end in\nsurance are included in a small\nmonthly payment. Or you can\nuse this plan to refinance a\nburdensome mortgage end reduce\nyour payments.\nYour problem will receive prompt\nattention, here, from home\nfinancing specialists.\nSAVINGSA1ft\n1337 G Street N.W.\n'RE. 5262\nBranch Takoma Park\na7~..-JT Mt\ng &ut66ecc\n^Finances\n(*tVl\u00bbCD\nTHE ORIGINAL\nLOOSE LEAF\nPERSONAL\nFINANCIAL SYSTEM\nETeryone should keep\nhis personal, financial\naffairs In order. !>Iy\nFinances! provides the\nsimplest, most complete\nand Ingenious system\never made for the pur\npose.\nSTOCKETT\nF I SICE CO\nPRODUCING STATIONERS\n9I9C ST\nPhone NAtional 917*","height":"31744","width":"22248"}}
